com.gdxgame.core

Class GDXGame

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.badlogic.gdx.Game
      • com.gdxgame.core.GDXGame
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ApplicationListener

    public class GDXGame
extends Game
    GDXGame is the entrypoint for each game made with libgdx. It extends the libgdx Game class to have the screen switching functionality available (check Screen class of libgdx). We use the Screen functionality to switch between game states

        public void create()

        public void render()
        automatically called by Game.render() method per frame. Each frame the entire screen is cleared by a specified color within the GameConstants. Updates and renders the current active game state.

      • setGameState

        public void setGameState(GameStateType newState,
                         boolean disposeActiveState,
                         boolean reinitializeExisting,
                         Object data)
        Changes the current gamestate to the given newState. If the passed newState parameter is null then the game will be closed.

        Creates the gamestate and the gamestate's logic instance that are defined in the GameStateType enum if the gamestate of type newState is not yet available in the gamestates stack. Otherwise the existing gamestate will be reused.

        To pause the active gamestate (f.e. to pause the game to switch to a menu) and put another gamestate on top, pass false for the disposeActiveState parameter. This will keep the current active gamestate in the gamestates stack and will ignore the GameState.dispose() call to this gamestate.

        When switching back to an already existing gamestate you can choose to reinitialize it (=calling its GameStateLogic.initialize() method) or to just continue updating/rendering. To reinizialite it pass true for reinitializeExisting parameter.
        Parameters:
        newState - new state that should get active. null to close the game.
        disposeActiveState - true to call the GameState.dispose() method of the current active gamestate and to remove it from the gameStates stack. false to keep the current active state in the gamestates stack and to avoid calling its GameState.dispose() method.
        reinitializeExisting - true to call GameStateLogic.initialize() method of already existing gamestate when switching to it false to ignore the GameStateLogic.initialize() call
        data - Data that will be forwarded to the active gamestate that is set with this call. Can be null.

      • isGameStateAvailable

        public boolean isGameStateAvailable(GameStateType type)
        Checks if a gamestate of type type is available in the gamestates stack.
        Parameters:

        Returns:
        true when a gamestate of type type was found. false otherwise.
